1) What is Amazon Route 53?
--> Amazon Route 53 is a DNS (Domain Name System) service provided by AWS.
It is used to register domains, route traffic to resources, and perform health checks.

2) What are the main features of Route 53?
Domain registration
DNS routing
Health checks and failover
Traffic management

3) What is a Hosted Zone in Route 53?
A hosted zone is a container for DNS records of a domain.
Public Hosted Zone – for internet-facing domains
Private Hosted Zone – for VPC internal domains

4) What are DNS record types supported by Route 53?
A – Maps domain to IPv4 address
AAAA – Maps domain to IPv6 address
CNAME – Maps one domain to another
Alias – AWS-specific record (ELB, S3, CloudFront)

5) What is an Alias record and why is it used?
Maps a domain to AWS resources (ELB, CloudFront, S3)
Does not charge for DNS queries
Supports root domain (example.com)

6) What routing policies are available in Route 53?
Simple
Weighted
Latency-based
Failover
Geolocation

7) What is Latency-based routing?
Latency routing sends user traffic to the AWS region with the lowest latency, improving performance.

8) What is Health Check in Route 53?
Health checks monitor the health of endpoints (EC2, ELB, IP).
If an endpoint fails, Route 53 can redirect traffic to a healthy resource.

9) How does Route 53 support high availability?
Route 53 provides high availability using:
Health checks
Failover routing policy
Multi-region traffic routing


